[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Automata theory is closely related to formal language theory.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] In this context, automata are used as finite representations of formal languages that may be infinite.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Automata are often classified by the class of formal languages they can recognize, as in the Chomsky hierarchy, which describes a nesting relationship between major classes of automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Automata play a major role in the theory of computation, compiler construction, artificial intelligence, parsing and formal verification.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The theory of abstract automata was developed in the mid-20th century in connection with finite automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Automata theory was initially considered a branch of mathematical systems theory, studying the behavior of discrete-parameter systems.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Early work in automata theory differed from previous work on systems by using abstract algebra to describe information systems rather than differential calculus to describe material systems.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The theory of the finite-state transducer was developed under different names by different research communities.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The earlier concept of Turing machine was also included in the discipline along with new forms of infinite-state automata, such as pushdown automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] 1956 saw the publication of *Automata Studies*, which collected work by scientists including Claude Shannon, W.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Ross Ashby, John von Neumann, Marvin Minsky, Edward F.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] With the publication of this volume, "automata theory emerged as a relatively autonomous discipline".
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The book included Kleene's description of the set of regular events, or regular languages, and a relatively stable measure of complexity in Turing machine programs by Shannon.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] In the same year, Noam Chomsky described the Chomsky hierarchy, a correspondence between automata and formal grammars, and Ross Ashby published *An Introduction to Cybernetics*, an accessible textbook explaining automata and information using basic set theory.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The study of linear bounded automata led to the Myhill–Nerode theorem, which gives a necessary and sufficient condition for a formal language to be regular, and an exact count of the number of states in a minimal machine for the language.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The pumping lemma for regular languages, also useful in regularity proofs, was proven in this period by Michael O.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Rabin and Dana Scott, along with the computational equivalence of deterministic and nondeterministic finite automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] In the 1960s, a body of algebraic results known as "structure theory" or "algebraic decomposition theory" emerged, which dealt with the realization of sequential machines from smaller machines by interconnection.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] While any finite automaton can be simulated using a universal gate set, this requires that the simulating circuit contain loops of arbitrary complexity.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Structure theory deals with the "loop-free" realizability of machines.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The theory of computational complexity also took shape in the 1960s.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] By the end of the decade, automata theory came to be seen as "the pure mathematics of computer science".
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] What follows is a general definition of an automaton, which restricts a broader definition of a system to one viewed as acting in discrete time-steps, with its state behavior and outputs defined at each step by unchanging functions of only its state and input.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] An automaton *runs* when it is given some sequence of *inputs* in discrete (individual) *time steps* (or just *steps*).
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] An automaton processes one input picked from a set of *symbols* or *letters*, which is called an *input alphabet*.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The symbols received by the automaton as input at any step are a sequence of symbols called *words*.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] At each moment during a run of the automaton, the automaton is *in* one of its states.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] When the automaton receives new input, it moves to another state (or *transitions*) based on a *transition function* that takes the previous state and current input symbol as parameters.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] At the same time, another function called the *output function* produces symbols from the *output alphabet*, also according to the previous state and current input symbol.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The automaton reads the symbols of the input word and transitions between states until the word is read completely, if it is finite in length, at which point the automaton *halts*.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] A state at which the automaton halts is called the *final state*.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] To investigate the possible state/input/output sequences in an automaton using formal language theory, a machine can be assigned a *starting state* and a set of *accepting states*.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Then, depending on whether a run starting from the starting state ends in an accepting state, the automaton can be said to *accept* or *reject* an input sequence.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The set of all the words accepted by an automaton is called the *language recognized by the automaton*.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] A familiar example of a machine recognizing a language is an electronic lock, which accepts or rejects attempts to enter the correct code.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] to describe the machine's behavior when fed whole input words.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] are the set of languages that are recognized by some automaton.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] For different types of automata, the recognizable languages are different.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Automata are defined to study useful machines under mathematical formalism.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] So the definition of an automaton is open to variations according to the "real world machine" that we want to model using the automaton.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] People have studied many variations of automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The following are some popular variations in the definition of different components of automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Different combinations of the above variations produce many classes of automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Automata theory is a subject matter that studies properties of various types of automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] For example, the following questions are studied about a given type of automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The following is an incomplete list of types of automata.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Normally automata theory describes the states of abstract machines but there are discrete automata, analog automata or continuous automata, or hybrid discrete-continuous automata, which use digital data, analog data or continuous time, or digital *and* analog data, respectively.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The following is an incomplete hierarchy in terms of powers of different types of virtual machines.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The hierarchy reflects the nested categories of languages the machines are able to accept.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Each model in automata theory plays important roles in several applied areas.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Finite automata are used in text processing, compilers, and hardware design.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Context-free grammar (CFGs) are used in programming languages and artificial intelligence.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Originally, CFGs were used in the study of human languages.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Cellular automata are used in the field of artificial life, the most famous example being John Conway's Game of Life.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Some other examples which could be explained using automata theory in biology include mollusk and pine cone growth and pigmentation patterns.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Going further, a theory suggesting that the whole universe is computed by some sort of a discrete automaton, is advocated by some scientists.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The idea originated in the work of Konrad Zuse, and was popularized in America by Edward Fredkin.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Automata also appear in the theory of finite fields: the set of irreducible polynomials that can be written as composition of degree two polynomials is in fact a regular language.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Another problem for which automata can be used is the induction of regular languages.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Automata simulators are pedagogical tools used to teach, learn and research automata theory.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] An automata simulator takes as input the description of an automaton and then simulates its working for an arbitrary input string.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The description of the automaton can be entered in several ways.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] An automaton can be defined in a symbolic language or its specification may be entered in a predesigned form or its transition diagram may be drawn by clicking and dragging the mouse.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Well known automata simulators include Turing's World, JFLAP, VAS, TAGS and SimStudio.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] One can define several distinct categories of automata following the automata classification into different types described in the previous section.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] The mathematical category of deterministic automata, sequential machines or *sequential automata*, and Turing machines with *automata homomorphisms* defining the arrows between automata is a Cartesian closed category, it has both categorical limits and colimits.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] An automata homomorphism maps a quintuple of an automaton *A**i* onto the quintuple of another automaton *A**j*.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Automata homomorphisms can also be considered as *automata transformations* or as semigroup homomorphisms, when the state space, ***S***, of the automaton is defined as a semigroup **S**g.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Monoids are also considered as a suitable setting for automata in monoidal categories.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] One could also define a *variable automaton*, in the sense of Norbert Wiener in his book on *The Human Use of Human Beings* *via* the endomorphisms $A_{i}\to A_{i}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Then one can show that such variable automata homomorphisms form a mathematical group.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] In the case of non-deterministic, or other complex kinds of automata, the latter set of endomorphisms may become, however, a *variable automaton groupoid*.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Therefore, in the most general case, categories of variable automata of any kind are categories of groupoids or groupoid categories.
[src:suffix-automaton/automata-theory] Moreover, the category of reversible automata is then a 2-category, and also a subcategory of the 2-category of groupoids, or the groupoid category.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] In computer science, a **deterministic acyclic finite state automaton** (**DAFSA**), is a data structure that represents a set of strings, and allows for a query operation that tests whether a given string belongs to the set in time proportional to its length.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Algorithms exist to construct and maintain such automata, while keeping them minimal.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] DAFSA is the rediscovery of a data structure called Directed Acyclic Word Graph (DAWG), although the same name had already been given to a different data structure which is related to suffix automaton.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] The strings represented by the DAFSA are formed by the symbols on paths in the graph from the source vertex to any sink vertex (a vertex with no outgoing edges).
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] In fact, a deterministic finite state automaton is acyclic if and only if it recognizes a finite set of strings.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Blumer et al first defined terminology Directed Acyclic Word Graph (DAWG) in 1983.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Appel and Jacobsen used the same naming for a different data structure in 1988.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Independent of earlier work, Daciuk et al rediscovered the latter data structure in 2000 but called it DAFSA.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] By allowing the same vertices to be reached by multiple paths, a DAFSA may use significantly fewer vertices than the strongly related trie data structure.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Consider, for example, the four English words "tap", "taps", "top", and "tops".
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] A trie for those four words would have 12 vertices, one for each of the strings formed as a prefix of one of these words, or for one of the words followed by the end-of-string marker.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] There is a tradeoff between memory and functionality, because a standard DAFSA can tell you if a word exists within it, but it cannot point you to auxiliary information about that word, whereas a trie can.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] The primary difference between DAFSA and trie is the elimination of suffix and infix redundancy in storing strings.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] The trie eliminates prefix redundancy since all common prefixes are shared between strings, such as between *doctors* and *doctorate* the *doctor* prefix is shared.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] In a DAFSA common suffixes are also shared, for words that have the same set of possible suffixes as each other.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] For dictionary sets of common English words, this translates into major memory usage reduction.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Because the terminal nodes of a DAFSA can be reached by multiple paths, a DAFSA cannot directly store auxiliary information relating to each path, e.g. a word's frequency in the English language.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] However, if for each node we store the number of unique paths through that point in the structure, we can use it to retrieve the index of a word, or a word given its index.
[src:suffix-automaton/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] The auxiliary information can then be stored in an array.
[src:suffix-automaton/factor-oracle] A **factor oracle** is a finite-state automaton that can efficiently search for factors (substrings) in a body of text.
[src:suffix-automaton/factor-oracle] Older techniques, such as suffix trees, were time-efficient but required significant amounts of memory.
[src:suffix-automaton/factor-oracle] Factor oracles, by contrast, can be constructed in linear time and space in an incremental fashion.
[src:suffix-automaton/factor-oracle] Older techniques for matching strings include: suffix arrays, suffix trees, suffix automata or directed acyclic word graphs, and factor automata (Allauzen, Crochemore, Raffinot, 1999).
[src:suffix-automaton/factor-oracle] In 1999, Allauzen, Crochemore, and Raffinot, presented the factor oracle algorithm as a memory efficient improvement upon these older techniques for string matching and compression.
[src:suffix-automaton/factor-oracle] Starting in the mid-2000s, factor oracles have found application in computer music, as well.
[src:suffix-automaton/factor-oracle] The Computer Audition Laboratory provides a Matlab implementation of the factor oracle algorithm.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] In computer science, a **generalized suffix tree** is a suffix tree for a set of strings.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] Given the set of strings $D=S_{1},S_{2},\dots ,S_{d}$ of total length n , it is a Patricia tree containing all n suffixes of the strings.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] It can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time and space, and can be used to find all z occurrences of a string P of length m in $O(m+z)$ time, which is asymptotically optimal (assuming the size of the alphabet is constant).
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] When constructing such a tree, each string should be padded with a unique out-of-alphabet marker symbol (or string) to ensure no suffix is a substring of another, guaranteeing each suffix is represented by a unique leaf node.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] Algorithms for constructing a GST include Ukkonen's algorithm (1995) and McCreight's algorithm (1976).
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] A suffix tree for the strings `ABAB` and `BABA` is shown in a figure above.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] They are padded with the unique terminator strings `$0` and `$1`.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] The numbers in the leaf nodes are string number and starting position.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] Notice how a left to right traversal of the leaf nodes corresponds to the sorted order of the suffixes.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] The terminators might be strings or unique single symbols.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] Edges on `$` from the root are left out in this example.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] An alternative to building a generalized suffix tree is to concatenate the strings, and build a regular suffix tree or suffix array for the resulting string.
[src:suffix-automaton/generalized-suffix-tree] When hits are evaluated after a search, global positions are mapped into documents and local positions with some algorithm and/or data structure, such as a binary search in the starting/ending positions of the documents.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In computer science, a **suffix automaton** is an efficient data structure for representing the substring index of a given string which allows the storage, processing, and retrieval of compressed information about all its substrings.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The suffix automaton of a string S is the smallest directed acyclic graph with a dedicated initial vertex and a set of "final" vertices, such that paths from the initial vertex to final vertices represent the suffixes of the string.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In terms of automata theory, a suffix automaton is the minimal partial deterministic finite automaton that recognizes the set of suffixes of a given string $S=s_{1}s_{2}\dots s_{n}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The state graph of a suffix automaton is called a directed acyclic word graph (DAWG), a term that is also sometimes used for any deterministic acyclic finite state automaton.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Suffix automata were introduced in 1983 by a group of scientists from the University of Denver and the University of Colorado Boulder.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] They suggested a linear time online algorithm for its construction and showed that the suffix automaton of a string S having length at least two characters has at most ${\textstyle 2|S|-1}$ states and at most ${\textstyle 3|S|-4}$ transitions.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Further works have shown a close connection between suffix automata and suffix trees, and have outlined several generalizations of suffix automata, such as compacted suffix automaton obtained by compression of nodes with a single outgoing arc.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Suffix automata provide efficient solutions to problems such as substring search and computation of the largest common substring of two and more strings.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In their initial work, Blumer *et al*. showed a suffix automaton built for the string S of length greater than 1 has at most $2|S|-1$ states and at most $3|S|-4$ transitions, and suggested a linear algorithm for automaton construction.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In 1983, Mu-Tian Chen and Joel Seiferas independently showed that Weiner's 1973 suffix-tree construction algorithm while building a suffix tree of the string S constructs a suffix automaton of the reversed string ${\textstyle S^{R}}$ as an auxiliary structure.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In 1987, Blumer *et al*. applied the compressing technique used in suffix trees to a suffix automaton and invented the compacted suffix automaton, which is also called the compacted directed acyclic word graph (CDAWG).
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In 1997, Maxime Crochemore and Renaud Vérin developed a linear algorithm for direct CDAWG construction.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In 2001, Shunsuke Inenaga *et al*. developed an algorithm for construction of CDAWG for a set of words given by a trie.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In terms of its diagram, the automaton recognizes the word $\omega =\omega _{1}\omega _{2}\dots \omega _{m}$ only if there is a path from the initial vertex $q_{0}$ to some final vertex $q\in F$ such that concatenation of characters on this path forms $\omega$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The set of words recognized by an automaton forms a language that is set to be recognized by the automaton.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In these terms, the language recognized by a suffix automaton of S is the language of its (possibly empty) suffixes.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] "Right context" of the word $\omega$ with respect to language L is a set $[\omega ]_{R}=\{\alpha :\omega \alpha \in L\}$ that is a set of words $\alpha$ such that their concatenation with $\omega$ forms a word from L .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Right contexts induce a natural equivalence relation $[\alpha ]_{R}=[\beta ]_{R}$ on the set of all words.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] If language L is recognized by some deterministic finite automaton, there exists unique up to isomorphism automaton that recognizes the same language and has the minimum possible number of states.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Such an automaton is called a minimal automaton for the given language L .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In these terms, a "suffix automaton" is the minimal deterministic finite automaton recognizing the language of suffixes of the word $S=s_{1}s_{2}\dots s_{n}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The right context of the word $\omega$ with respect to this language consists of words $\alpha$ , such that $\omega \alpha$ is a suffix of S .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] For example, for the word $S=abacaba$ and its subword $\omega =ab$ , it holds $endpos(ab)=\{2,6\}$ and $[ab]_{R}=\{a,acaba\}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Informally, $[ab]_{R}$ is formed by words that follow occurrences of $ab$ to the end of S and $endpos(ab)$ is formed by right positions of those occurrences.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In this example, the element $x=2\in endpos(ab)$ corresponds with the word $s_{3}s_{4}s_{5}s_{6}s_{7}=acaba\in [ab]_{R}$ while the word $a\in [ab]_{R}$ corresponds with the element $7-|a|=6\in endpos(ab)$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It implies several structure properties of suffix automaton states.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Any state $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ of the suffix automaton recognizes some continuous chain of nested suffixes of the longest word recognized by this state.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] "Left extension" ${\overset {\scriptstyle {\leftarrow }}{\gamma }}$ of the string $\gamma$ is the longest string $\omega$ that has the same right context as $\gamma$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Length $|{\overset {\scriptstyle {\leftarrow }}{\gamma }}|$ of the longest string recognized by $q=[\gamma ]_{R}$ is denoted by $len(q)$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] "Suffix link" $link(q)$ of the state $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ is the pointer to the state p that contains the largest suffix of $\alpha$ that is not recognized by q .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In this terms it can be said $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ recognizes exactly all suffixes of ${\overset {\scriptstyle {\leftarrow }}{\alpha }}$ that is longer than $len(link(q))$ and not longer than $len(q)$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Edges E of the tree connect pairs of vertices $({\overleftarrow {\omega }},{\overleftarrow {\alpha \omega }})$ , such that $\alpha \in \Sigma$ and ${\overleftarrow {\omega }}\neq {\overleftarrow {\alpha \omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] A "prefix tree" (or "trie") is a rooted directed tree in which arcs are marked by characters in such a way no vertex v of such tree has two out-going arcs marked with the same character.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Some vertices in trie are marked as final.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Trie is said to recognize a set of words defined by paths from its root to final vertices.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In this way prefix trees are a special kind of deterministic finite automata if you perceive its root as an initial vertex.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The "suffix trie" of the word S is a prefix tree recognizing a set of its suffixes.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] "A suffix tree" is a tree obtained from a suffix trie via the compaction procedure, during which consequent edges are merged if the degree of the vertex between them is equal to two.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] By its definition, a suffix automaton can be obtained via minimization of the suffix trie.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It may be shown that a compacted suffix automaton is obtained by both minimization of the suffix tree (if one assumes each string on the edge of the suffix tree is a solid character from the alphabet) and compaction of the suffix automaton.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Besides this connection between the suffix tree and the suffix automaton of the same string there is as well a connection between the suffix automaton of the string $S=s_{1}s_{2}\dots s_{n}$ and the suffix tree of the reversed string $S^{R}=s_{n}s_{n-1}\dots s_{1}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] A suffix automaton of the string S of length $n>1$ has at most $2n-1$ states and at most $3n-4$ transitions.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] These bounds are reached on strings $abb\dots bb=ab^{n-1}$ and $abb\dots bc=ab^{n-2}c$ correspondingly.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] This may be formulated in a stricter way as $|\delta |\leq |Q|+n-2$ where $|\delta |$ and $|Q|$ are the numbers of transitions and states in automaton correspondingly.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Initially the automaton only consists of a single state corresponding to the empty word, then characters of the string are added one by one and the automaton is rebuilt on each step incrementally.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] After a new character is appended to the string, some equivalence classes are altered.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Let $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ be the right context of $\alpha$ with respect to the language of $\omega$ suffixes.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] After adding x to the current word $\omega$ the right context of $\alpha$ may change significantly only if $\alpha$ is a suffix of $\omega x$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It implies equivalence relation $\equiv _{R_{\omega x}}$ is a refinement of $\equiv _{R_{\omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] After the addition of a new character at most two equivalence classes of $\equiv _{R_{\omega }}$ will be split and each of them may split in at most two new classes.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] First, equivalence class corresponding to empty right context is always split into two equivalence classes, one of them corresponding to $\omega x$ itself and having $\{\varepsilon \}$ as a right context.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] This new equivalence class contains exactly $\omega x$ and all its suffixes that did not occur in $\omega$ , as the right context of such words was empty before and contains only empty word now.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Given the correspondence between states of the suffix automaton and vertices of the suffix tree, it is possible to find out the second state that may possibly split after a new character is appended.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The transition from $\omega$ to $\omega x$ corresponds to the transition from $\omega ^{R}$ to $x\omega ^{R}$ in the reversed string.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In terms of suffix trees it corresponds to the insertion of the new longest suffix $x\omega ^{R}$ into the suffix tree of $\omega ^{R}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] At most two new vertices may be formed after this insertion: one of them corresponding to $x\omega ^{R}$ , while the other one corresponds to its direct ancestor if there was a branching.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Returning to suffix automata, it means the first new state recognizes $\omega x$ and the second one (if there is a second new state) is its suffix link.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It implies that if $\alpha =\beta$ (for example, when x didn't occur in $\omega$ at all and $\alpha =\beta =\varepsilon$ ), then only the equivalence class corresponding to the empty right context is split.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Besides suffix links it is also needed to define final states of the automaton.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It follows from structure properties that all suffixes of a word $\alpha$ recognized by $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ are recognized by some vertex on *suffix path* $(q,link(q),link^{2}(q),\dots )$ of q .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Namely, suffixes with length greater than $len(link(q))$ lie in q , suffixes with length greater than $len(link(link(q))$ but not greater than $len(link(q))$ lie in $link(q)$ and so on.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Thus if the state recognizing $\omega$ is denoted by $last$ , then all final states (that is, recognizing suffixes of $\omega$ ) form up the sequence $(last,link(last),link^{2}(last),\dots )$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] After the character x is appended to $\omega$ possible new states of suffix automaton are $[\omega x]_{R_{\omega x}}$ and $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Words from $[\omega x]_{R_{\omega x}}$ occur in $\omega x$ only as its suffixes therefore there should be no transitions at all from $[\omega x]_{R_{\omega x}}$ while transitions to it should go from suffixes of $\omega$ having length at least $\alpha$ and be marked with the character x .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] State $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ is formed by subset of $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ , thus transitions from $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ should be same as from $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Meanwhile, transitions leading to $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ should go from suffixes of $\omega$ having length less than $|\alpha |$ and at least $len(link([\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}))$ , as such transitions have led to $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ before and corresponded to seceded part of this state.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] States corresponding to these suffixes may be determined via traversal of suffix link path for $[\omega ]_{R_{\omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] States corresponding to suffixes of ω are updated with transitions to last.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Transitions that have led to q before but corresponded to words of the length at most $len(p)+1$ are redirected to cl.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] To do this, one continues going through the suffix path of p until the state is found such that transition by x from it doesn't lead to q.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Here $q_{0}$ is the initial state of the automaton and `new_state()` is a function creating new state for it.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It is assumed `*last*`, `*len*`, `*link*` and `δ` are stored as global variables.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] For convenience, `*link(q0)*` is defined to be $q_{0}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Complexity of the algorithm may vary depending on the underlying structure used to store transitions of the automaton.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It may be implemented in $O(n\log |\Sigma |)$ with $O(n)$ memory overhead or in $O(n)$ with $O(n|\Sigma |)$ memory overhead if one assumes that memory allocation is done in $O(1)$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] To obtain such complexity, one has to use the methods of amortized analysis.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The value of $len(p)$ strictly reduces with each iteration of the cycle while it may only increase by as much as one after the first iteration of the cycle on the next *add_letter* call.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Overall value of $len(p)$ never exceeds n and it is only increased by one between iterations of appending new letters that suggest total complexity is at most linear as well.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The linearity of the second cycle is shown in a similar way.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The suffix automaton is closely related to other suffix structures and substring indices.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Given a suffix automaton of a specific string one may construct its suffix tree via compacting and recursive traversal in linear time.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Similar transforms are possible in both directions to switch between the suffix automaton of S and the suffix tree of reversed string $S^{R}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] As was already mentioned above, a compacted suffix automaton is obtained via both compaction of a regular suffix automaton (by removing states which are non-final and have exactly one out-going arc) and the minimization of a suffix tree.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Similarly to the regular suffix automaton, states of compacted suffix automaton may be defined in explicit manner.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] *A two-way extension* ${\overset {\scriptstyle {\longleftrightarrow }}{\gamma }}$ of a word $\gamma$ is the longest word $\omega =\beta \gamma \alpha$ , such that every occurrence of $\gamma$ in S is preceded by $\beta$ and succeeded by $\alpha$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Two-way extensions induce an equivalence relation ${\textstyle {\overset {\scriptstyle \longleftrightarrow }{\alpha }}={\overset {\scriptstyle \longleftrightarrow }{\beta }}}$ which defines the set of words recognized by the same state of compacted automaton.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] If words $\alpha$ and $\beta$ have same right extensions, and words $\beta$ and $\gamma$ have same left extensions, then cumulatively all strings $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\gamma$ have same two-way extensions.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] At the same time it may happen that neither left nor right extensions of $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ coincide.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The total number of equivalence classes for this relation does not exceed $n+1$ which implies that compacted suffix automaton of the string having length n has at most $n+1$ states.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The amount of transitions in such automaton is at most $2n-2$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It is possible to construct a generalization of suffix automaton that would recognize the language formed up by suffixes of all words from the set.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Constraints for the number of states and transitions in such automaton would stay the same as for a single-word automaton if you put $n=|S_{1}|+|S_{2}|+\dots +|S_{k}|$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] This idea is further generalized to the case when T is not given explicitly but instead is given by a prefix tree with Q vertices.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Mohri *et al*. showed such an automaton would have at most $2Q-2$ and may be constructed in linear time from its size.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Some compression algorithms, such as LZ77 and RLE may benefit from storing suffix automaton or similar structure not for the whole string but for only last k its characters while the string is updated.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] This is because compressing data is usually expressively large and using $O(n)$ memory is undesirable.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] In 1985, Janet Blumer developed an algorithm to maintain a suffix automaton on a sliding window of size k in $O(nk)$ worst-case and $O(n\log k)$ on average, assuming characters are distributed independently and uniformly.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] A variation of McCreight's suffix tree construction algorithm for this task was suggested in 1989 by Edward Fiala and Daniel Greene; several years later a similar result was obtained with the variation of Ukkonen's algorithm by Jesper Larsson.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] One way to overcome this obstacle is to allow window width to vary a bit while staying $O(k)$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It may be achieved by an approximate algorithm suggested by Inenaga et al. in 2004.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] The window for which suffix automaton is built in this algorithm is not guaranteed to be of length k but it is guaranteed to be at least k and at most $2k+1$ while providing linear overall complexity of the algorithm.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] It is assumed here that T is given on the input after suffix automaton of S is constructed.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-automaton] Suffix automata are also used in data compression, music retrieval and matching on genome sequences.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] In computer science, a **suffix tree** (also called **PAT tree** or, in an earlier form, **position tree**) is a compressed trie containing all the suffixes of the given text as their keys and positions in the text as their values.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Suffix trees allow particularly fast implementations of many important string operations.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The construction of such a tree for the string S takes time and space linear in the length of S .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Once constructed, several operations can be performed quickly, such as locating a substring in S , locating a substring if a certain number of mistakes are allowed, and locating matches for a regular expression pattern.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Suffix trees also provided one of the first linear-time solutions for the longest common substring problem.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] These speedups come at a cost: storing a string's suffix tree typically requires significantly more space than storing the string itself.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The concept was first introduced by Weiner (1973).
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Rather than the suffix $S[i..n]$ , Weiner stored in his trie the *prefix identifier* for each position, that is, the shortest string starting at i and occurring only once in S .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] His *Algorithm D* takes an uncompressed trie for $S[k+1..n]$ and extends it into a trie for $S[k..n]$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] This way, starting from the trivial trie for $S[n..n]$ , a trie for $S[1..n]$ can be built by $n-1$ successive calls to Algorithm D; however, the overall run time is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Weiner's *Algorithm B* maintains several auxiliary data structures, to achieve an overall run time linear in the size of the constructed trie.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The latter can still be $O(n^{2})$ nodes, e.g. for $S=a^{n}b^{n}a^{n}b^{n}\$.$ Weiner's *Algorithm C* finally uses compressed tries to achieve linear overall storage size and run time.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Donald Knuth subsequently characterized the latter as "Algorithm of the Year 1973" according to his student Vaughan Pratt.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The text book Aho, Hopcroft & Ullman (1974, Sect.9.5) reproduced Weiner's results in a simplified and more elegant form, introducing the term *position tree*.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] McCreight (1976) was the first to build a (compressed) trie of all suffixes of S .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Although the suffix starting at i is usually longer than the prefix identifier, their path representations in a compressed trie do not differ in size.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] On the other hand, McCreight could dispense with most of Weiner's auxiliary data structures; only suffix links remained.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Ukkonen (1995) further simplified the construction.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] He provided the first online-construction of suffix trees, now known as Ukkonen's algorithm, with running time that matched the then fastest algorithms.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] These algorithms are all linear-time for a constant-size alphabet, and have worst-case running time of $O(n\log n)$ in general.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Farach (1997) gave the first suffix tree construction algorithm that is optimal for all alphabets.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] In particular, this is the first linear-time algorithm for strings drawn from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Farach's algorithm has become the basis for new algorithms for constructing both suffix trees and suffix arrays, for example, in external memory, compressed, succinct, etc.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Except for the root, every internal node has at least two children.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Each edge is labelled with a non-empty substring of S .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] No two edges starting out of a node can have string-labels beginning with the same character.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The string obtained by concatenating all the string-labels found on the path from the root to leaf i spells out suffix $S[i..n]$ , for i from 1 to n .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] If a suffix of S is also the prefix of another suffix, such a tree does not exist for the string.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] For example, in the string *abcbc*, the suffix *bc* is also a prefix of the suffix *bcbc*.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] In such a case, the path spelling out *bc* will not end in a leaf, violating the fifth rule.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] To fix this problem, S is padded with a terminal symbol not seen in the string (usually denoted `$`).
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] This ensures that no suffix is a prefix of another, and that there will be n leaf nodes, one for each of the n suffixes of S .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Since all internal non-root nodes are branching, there can be at most $n-1$ such nodes, and $n+(n-1)+1=2n$ nodes in total ( n leaves, $n-1$ internal non-root nodes, 1 root).
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] A generalized suffix tree is a suffix tree made for a set of strings instead of a single string.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] It represents all suffixes from this set of strings.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Each string must be terminated by a different termination symbol.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] A suffix tree for a string S of length n can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, if the letters come from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range (in particular, this is true for constant-sized alphabets).
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] For larger alphabets, the running time is dominated by first sorting the letters to bring them into a range of size $O(n)$ ; in general, this takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The costs below are given under the assumption that the alphabet is constant.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Assume that a suffix tree has been built for the string S of length n , or that a generalised suffix tree has been built for the set of strings $D=\{S_{1},S_{2},\dots ,S_{K}\}$ of total length $n=n_{1}+n_{2}+\cdots +n_{K}$ .
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The suffix tree can be prepared for constant time lowest common ancestor retrieval between nodes in $\Theta (n)$ time.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Suffix trees can be used to solve a large number of string problems that occur in text-editing, free-text search, computational biology and other application areas.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are often used in bioinformatics applications, searching for patterns in DNA or protein sequences (which can be viewed as long strings of characters).
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The ability to search efficiently with mismatches might be considered their greatest strength.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are also used in data compression; they can be used to find repeated data, and can be used for the sorting stage of the Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Variants of the LZW compression schemes use suffix trees (LZSS).
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] A suffix tree is also used in suffix tree clustering, a data clustering algorithm used in some search engines.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] If each node and edge can be represented in $\Theta (1)$ space, the entire tree can be represented in $\Theta (n)$ space.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The total length of all the strings on all of the edges in the tree is $O(n^{2})$ , but each edge can be stored as the position and length of a substring of S, giving a total space usage of $\Theta (n)$ computer words.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The worst-case space usage of a suffix tree is seen with a fibonacci word, giving the full $2n$ nodes.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] An important choice when making a suffix tree implementation is the parent-child relationships between nodes.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The most common is using linked lists called **sibling lists**.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Each node has a pointer to its first child, and to the next node in the child list it is a part of.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Other implementations with efficient running time properties use hash maps, sorted or unsorted arrays (with array doubling), or balanced search trees.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The insertion cost is amortised, and that the costs for hashing are given for perfect hashing.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The large amount of information in each edge and node makes the suffix tree very expensive, consuming about 10 to 20 times the memory size of the source text in good implementations.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Researchers have continued to find smaller indexing structures.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Various parallel algorithms to speed up suffix tree construction have been proposed.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Recently, a practical parallel algorithm for suffix tree construction with $O(n)$ work (sequential time) and $O(\log ^{2}n)$ span has been developed.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The algorithm achieves good parallel scalability on shared-memory multicore machines and can index the human genome – approximately 3GB – in under 3 minutes using a 40-core machine.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] Though linear, the memory usage of a suffix tree is significantly higher than the actual size of the sequence collection.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] For a large text, construction may require external memory approaches.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] There are theoretical results for constructing suffix trees in external memory.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The algorithm by Farach-Colton, Ferragina & Muthukrishnan (2000) is theoretically optimal, with an I/O complexity equal to that of sorting.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] However the overall intricacy of this algorithm has prevented, so far, its practical implementation.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] On the other hand, there have been practical works for constructing disk-based suffix trees which scale to (few) GB/hours.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The state of the art methods are TDD, TRELLIS, DiGeST, and B2ST.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] TDD and TRELLIS scale up to the entire human genome resulting in a disk-based suffix tree of a size in the tens of gigabytes.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] However, these methods cannot handle efficiently collections of sequences exceeding 3 GB.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] DiGeST performs significantly better and is able to handle collections of sequences in the order of 6 GB in about 6 hours.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] All these methods can efficiently build suffix trees for the case when the tree does not fit in main memory, but the input does.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] The most recent method, B2ST, scales to handle inputs that do not fit in main memory.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] ERA is a recent parallel suffix tree construction method that is significantly faster.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] ERA can index the entire human genome in 19 minutes on an 8-core desktop computer with 16 GB RAM.
[src:suffix-automaton/suffix-tree] On a simple Linux cluster with 16 nodes (4 GB RAM per node), ERA can index the entire human genome in less than 9 minutes.
